22 film)]], starring John Barrymore\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (1931 film series)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (1931 film series)]], starring Arthur Wontner\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (1932 film)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (1932 film)]], starring Clive Brook\n*[[The Grey Lady (film)|''The Grey Lady'' (film)]], also known as ''Sherlock Holmes'', a 1937 German mystery film\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (1939 film series)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (1939 film series)]], starring Basil Rathbone and Nigel Bruce\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (2009 film)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (2009 film)]], starring Robert Downey, Jr. and Jude Law\n**[[Sherlock Holmes (soundtrack)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (soundtrack)]], the soundtrack album\n*''[[Sherlock Holmes: A Game of Shadows]]'', the 2011 sequel to the 2009 film\n**[[Sherlock Holmes: A Game of Shadows (soundtrack)|''Sherlock Holmes: A Game of Shadows'' (soundtrack)]]\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (2010 film)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (2010 film)]], a direct-to-DVD film starring Ben Syder and Gareth David-Lloyd\n\n==Novels==\n*''[[Sherlock Holmes of Baker Street]]'', a 1962 novel by William S. Baring-Gould\n*''[[Sherlock Holmes: The Unauthorized Biography]]'', a 2005 novel by Nick Rennison\n\n== Television ==\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (1951 TV series)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (1951 TV series)]], a BBC production starring Alan Wheatley\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (1954 TV series)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (1954 TV series)]], an American production, filmed in France, starring Ronald Howard\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (1965 TV series)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (1965 TV series)]], a British production with Peter Cushing and Douglas Wilmer portraying Holmes in different years\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (1967 TV series)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (1967 TV series)]], a German production starring Erich Schellow\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (1968 TV series)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (1968 TV series)]], an Italian production starring Nando Gazzolo\n*''[[Sherlock Holmes and Doctor Watson]]'', a Polish-American production starring Geoffrey Whitehead and Donald Pickering\n*''[[The Adventures of Sherlock Holmes and Dr. Watson]]'' (1979-1986 TV series), [[Soviet]] adaptation starring MBE [[Vasily Livanov]].\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (1984 TV series)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (1984 TV series)]], a British production starring Jeremy Brett\n*[[Sherlock (TV series)|''Sherlock'' (TV series)]], a 2010 BBC one production starring Benedict Cumberbatch and Martin Freeman\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (2013 TV series)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (2013 TV series)]], a Russian television adaptation\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (2014 TV series)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (2014 TV series)]], a 2014 Japanese puppetry TV series written by Koki Mitani\n\n==Theatre== <!-- Leave it in British spelling. Thank you. -->\n*[[Sherlock Holmes (play)|''Sherlock Holmes'' (play)]], an 1899 play written by and starring William Gillette\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Holmes and Watson (disambiguation)]]\n*[[The Sherlock Holmes]], a public house in Northumberland Street, London\n*[[Adaptations of Sherlock Holmes]]\n*[[List of adaptations of Sherlock Holmes]]\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "name_user": "Ubcule", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision:Delinked, only links directly related to purpose of dab should be included on dab pages", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sherlock_Holmes_(disambiguation)"}
{"title_page": "Padiham", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|static_image_name=         Padiham Town Hall.jpg\n|static_image_caption=      Padiham Town Hall in 1994,<br />designed by [[Bradshaw Gass & Hope]] 1938\n| official_name=            Padiham\n| country=                  England\n| region=                   North West England\n| area_total_sq_mi=         {{convert|636.11|ha|mi2|2|disp=number}}\n| area_footnotes=           <ref name=pop/>\n| population=               10,098\n| population_ref=           ''(2011)'' <ref name=pop/>\n| os_grid_reference=        SD7933\n| coordinates=              {{coord|53.797|-2.311|display=inline,title}}\n| post_town=                BURNLEY\n| postcode_area=            BB\n| postcode_district=        BB12\n| dial_code=                01282\n| civil_parish=             Padiham\n| shire_district=           [[Burnley (borough)|Burnley]]\n| shire_county=             [[Lancashire]]\n| constituency_westminster= [[Burnley (UK Parliament constituency)|Burnley]]\n| pushpin_map=              United Kingdom Borough of Burnley\n| pushpin_map_caption=      Shown within Burnley Borough\n}}\n\n<!----------IMAGES--------->\n[[File:Church Street Padiham.jpg|thumb|right|256px|Church Street looking north from St Leonard's, c.&nbsp;1900. The Old Black Bull is next to the church. The view has hardly changed, but unlike some others, the street is no longer [[cobblestones|cobbled]].]]\n[[File:St Leonard's Church, Padiham, from Guy Street.jpg|thumb|right|256px|St Leonard's Church, from Guy Street]]\n[[File:Gawthorpe new.jpg|thumb|right|256px|[[Gawthorpe Hall]] in Padiham. Owned by\n[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] but jointly managed with [[Lancashire County Council]].]]\n<!----------IMAGES END----->\n\n'''Padiham''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|\u00e6|d|i|\u0259|m}} {{respell|PAD|i|\u0259m}}) is a small town and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] on the [[River Calder, Lancashire|River Calder]], about {{convert|3|mi|km|0|spell=in}} west of [[Burnley]] and south of [[Pendle Hill]], in [[Lancashire, England|Lancashire]], England. It is part of the [[Burnley (borough)|Borough of Burnley]], but has its own [[Town Council#United Kingdom|town council]] with varied powers. Padiham was originally a rural village lying by the River Calder. It is still surrounded by attractive countryside on an arc running from the north-west to the north-east in the foothills of Pendle Hill.\n\nAccording to the [[United Kingdom Census 2011]], the parish has a population of 10,098,<ref name=pop>{{NOMIS2011|id=1170214988|title=Padiham Parish|accessdate=8 February 2018}}\n</ref> an increase from 8,998 in the 2001 census.<ref>[http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790436 Office for National Statistics : ''Census 2001 : Parish Headcounts : Burnley''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202328/http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790436 |date=3 March 2016 }} Retrieved 4 February 2010</ref>\n\n==History==\nNo prehistoric or [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] sites have been found in the urban area and Padiham, a name of [[Anglo-Saxon]] origin, is not recorded in the [[Domesday Book]].<ref name=\"LCC Survey\">[http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/environment/documents/historictowns/PadihamComplete_LowRes.pdf Historic Town Assessment Report, Padiham, Lancashire County Council, May 2005, includes several old maps of the town and location of buildings \u2013 accessed 18 August 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001080455/http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/environment/documents/historictowns/PadihamComplete_LowRes.pdf |date=1 October 2012 }}</ref> The first recorded mention of the town, as ''Padyngham'', dates from 1294.<ref>[http://www.visitburnley.com/padiham.php About Padiham Accessed 4 February 2010]</ref> For hundreds of years it was a market town where produce from [[Pendle Hill|Pendleside]] was bought and sold. The town expanded and was substantially redeveloped during the [[Industrial Revolution]] and the central area is now a [[conservation area]].\n\nPadiham's population peaked around 1921 at about 14,000 declining to 10,000 in the early 1960s and 8,998 at the time of the 2001 census.<ref name=VoB/><ref>[http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=795670&c=padiham&d=16&e=15&g=461314&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1197124485873&enc=1&dsFamilyId=779 2001 census data]. Accessed 8 December 2007</ref> This follows people moving to the south of England in search of work following the decline of the traditional cotton, coal and engineering manufacturing base during that period.\n\nThe [[Queen Elizabeth II|Queen]], together with [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]], first visited [[Burnley]], [[Nelson, Lancashire|Nelson]] and the old [[Mullard]] valve factory at [[Simonstone, Lancashire|Simonstone]] near Padiham on her post-[[Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II|Coronation]] tour of Lancashire in 1955.<ref name = \"Pathe\">[http://www.britishpathe.com/video/royal-tour-of-lancashire-1/query/Queen+Elizabeth+Burnley British Path\u00e9 Newsreel 1995 Accessed 2014_02_01]</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nPadiham was once a [[Township (England)|township]] in the ancient parish of Whalley. This became a [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in 1866.<ref name=VoB>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit/10375502/relationships|title=Padiham Ch/CP through time|publisher=GB Historical GIS / University of Portsmouth|work=visionofbritain.org.uk|accessdate=18 October 2013}}</ref> An [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]] covered the town from 1894 (until 1974), however at this time the rural areas mainly to the north became a new civil parish called Northtown, forming part of the [[Burnley Rural District]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit/10374121/relationships|title=Northtown CP through time|publisher=GB Historical GIS / University of Portsmouth|work=visionofbritain.org.uk|accessdate=18 October 2013}}</ref> But the Padiham Green area, previously part of Hapton,{{efn|name=Hapton|The old township boundary with [[Hapton, Lancashire|Hapton]] followed the [[River Calder, Lancashire|River Calder]] and its tributary [[Green Brook, Lancashire|Green Brook]].<ref name=OS>{{Cite map |publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]] |title=Lancashire and Furness |series=County Series |scale=1 : 10,560 |edition=1st |year=1848}}</ref>}} transferred to Padiham with another small area following in 1935.<ref name=VoB/> Since 1974 Padiham has formed part of the [[Borough of Burnley]]. A [[Town Council]] was established in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.padihamtowncouncil.gov.uk/html/about_us.html|title=Padiham Town Council \u2013 About us|accessdate=13 October 2013|publisher=Padiham Town Council|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019141521/http://www.padihamtowncouncil.gov.uk/html/about_us.html|archivedate=19 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCouncillors for Padiham on [[Borough of Burnley|Burnley Borough Council]] are elected to the [[Gawthorpe Ward]], which covers most of Padiham but not [[Gawthorpe Hall]],<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Ordnance Survey |title=Gawthorpe |website=Ordnance Survey Linked Data Platform |url=http://data.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/doc/7000000000004603 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> with the southern and eastern areas covered by the Hapton with Park Ward.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Ordnance Survey |title=Hapton with Park |website=Ordnance Survey Linked Data Platform |url=http://data.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/doc/7000000000004619 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> Burnley Borough Council now addresses public correspondence to both the people of Burnley and Padiham. Padiham is part of [[Lancashire County Council]] and the Parliamentary Constituency is [[Burnley (UK Parliament constituency)|Burnley]] currently represented by [[Antony Higginbotham]] for the Conservative Party.\n\n==Economy==\nIn the 19th century, Padiham's industry was based on [[coal-mining]] and [[Mill town|weaving]]. Helm Mill on Factory Lane was the first mill built in 1807. By 1906 there were twenty [[cotton mill]]s<ref name = \"Pevsner\">{{cite book | author=Pevsner, Nikolaus; Hartwell, Clare (revision)| title=The Buildings of England \u2013 Lancashire: North| year=2009 | publisher=Yale University Press | location=London and New Haven | isbn=978-0-300-12667-9 | pages=490\u2013496}}</ref> though the best preserved, now converted into flats, is Victoria Mill, built 1852\u201353 with an 1873 extension, in Ightenhill Street.<ref name = \"Pevsner\"/>  Many local cotton workers were members of the [[Padiham Weavers' Association]], the membership of which peaked in 1907 at more than 6,000.<ref name=\"marsh\">{{cite book|last1=Marsh|first1=Arthur|last2=Ryan|first2=Victoria|last3=Smethurst|first3=John B.|title=Historical Directory of Trade Unions|volume=4|date=1994|publisher=Ashgate|location=Farnham|isbn=9780859679008|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historicaldirect0004mars/page/114 114]|url=https://archive.org/details/historicaldirect0004mars/page/114}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Report on Trade Unions in 1905-1907|date=1909|publisher=Board of Trade|location=London|pages=82\u2013101}}</ref>\n\nIndustrial development was helped by the proximity of the [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]] about {{convert|2|mi|km|1}} south. By 1848, Padiham had many coal pits around the town, including two large collieries and a number of smaller workings. The availability of coal and water nearby helped the development of the cotton industry in the town.<ref name = \"LCC Survey\"/> The arrival of the railway at [[Hapton, Lancashire|Hapton]] in 1840 and Padiham itself in 1877 further boosted industry in the town.<ref name = \"LCC Survey\"/> The last pit closed around 1870,<ref>[http://www.padihamlife.co.uk/about/mining.htm Padiham Life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828155231/http://www.padihamlife.co.uk/about/mining.htm |date=28 August 2008 }}</ref> although mining continued in areas outside the town into the 1950s and [[open cast mining]] took place in the 1960s east of the town close to Gawthorpe Hall but north of the River Calder off Grove Lane.\n\nSince the 1960s the remaining cotton mills have also continued a decline which began in the 1930s. Padiham's second role as a manufacturing base has also been in decline since the 1990s. The town's last major employer in this sector, [[Baxi]], closed its factory in March 2007 with the loss of 500 jobs.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/lancashire/6453773.stm '' 'Job Threat After Factory Closure' '', BBC News website 15 March 2007, accessed 14 January 2008]</ref> A modern business park, ''Shuttleworth Mead'',<ref>[http://www.ribbleindustrialestatesltd.co.uk/ Shuttleworth Mead Business Park]. Accessed 5 September 2008</ref> opened in 2001 on the western edge of the town on the site of the old [[Padiham Power Station]]<ref>[http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/corporate/web/?REMADE/20211 Lancashire County Council proposals for public footpath July 2009, Accessed 11 February 2010] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120804143825/http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/corporate/web/?REMADE/20211 |date=4 August 2012 }}</ref> which closed in 1993, supported by \u00a32.2&nbsp;million from the [[European Regional Development Fund]] and \u00a32&nbsp;million from the [[Regional Development Agency|North West Development Agency]].<ref>[http://nwda.co.uk/ North West Regional Development Agency]. Accessed 6 September 2008</ref> Tenants include Supanet, an internet service provider ([[ISP]]) and Graham & Brown, a wallcoverings company.\n\nIn 2007 Fort Vale Engineering moved into the old [[Mullard]]/Philips site at Calder Vale Park, [[Simonstone, Lancashire|Simonstone]] which had closed in 2004, and developed a new purpose-built factory. Fort Vale Engineering employs around 280 people from around the local area and has brought new business to other local employers.\n\n==Landmarks==\n\nThere are five significant halls in the local area: [[Huntroyde Hall]],<ref name=\"Hunt\">[http://www.parksandgardens.ac.uk/component/option,com_parksandgardens/task,site/id,5227/Itemid,292/ Parks and Gardens UK \u2013 based on the English Heritage Register of Parks and Gardens of Special Historic Interest] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226091547/http://www.parksandgardens.ac.uk/component/option,com_parksandgardens/task,site/id,5227/Itemid,292/ |date=26 February 2012 }}</ref> dating from 1576, and [[Simonstone, Lancashire#Simonstone Hall|Simonstone Hall]], dating from 1660, in nearby [[Simonstone, Lancashire|Simonstone]], are both privately owned. [[Gawthorpe Hall]] was donated to the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] in 1970 but is jointly managed with [[Lancashire County Council]], which has a 99-year lease. Gawthorpe is in the [[Ightenhill]] district.<ref>[http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-gawthorpehall National Trust Website, accessed 2 October 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080921232519/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-gawthorpehall |date=21 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe Trust also runs an office and a tea room in the courtyard of the property.<ref>[http://www.r-alston.co.uk/ch_eng.htm Searchable guide to country houses, includes Gawthorpe and other houses owned by the Shuttleworths \u2013 accessed 18 April 2010] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040204052356/http://www.r-alston.co.uk/ch_eng.htm |date=4 February 2004 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Padiham/ www.genuki.org.uk] Accessed 13 November 2007</ref> Gawthorpe was the family home of the Shuttleworth family who occupied [[Shuttleworth Hall]] near Hapton from the 12th century.<ref>[http://www.grimshaworigin.org/WebPages/ShutGawt.htm Grimshaw and Shuttleworth family origin website, accessed 15 January 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228171757/http://www.grimshaworigin.org/WebPages/ShutGawt.htm |date=28 December 2012 }}</ref><ref name = \"Pevsner2\">{{Cite book | author=Pevsner, Nikolaus; Hartwell, Clare (revision)| title=The Buildings of England \u2013 Lancashire: North| year=2009 | publisher=Yale University Press | location=London and New Haven | isbn=978-0-300-12667-9 | page=321}}</ref> The current building dates from 1639 and is still a working farm. [[Read Hall and Park]] is in the nearby village of [[Read, Lancashire|Read]], about {{convert|1|mi|km|1}} west of Padiham on the [[A671 road|A671]].\n\n[[File:St Matthews Padiham 2007-12-12.jpg|thumb|right|256px|St Leonard's Parish Church]]\nSt Leonard's Church, the town's parish church, dates from 1866\u201369 and is a [[Grade II listed building]].<ref>[http://lfhhs-pendleandburnley.org.uk/church/xpad1.htm Lancashire Family History & Heraldry Society]. Accessed 13 November 2007</ref> It was built on the site of earlier churches dating back to at least 1451.<ref name=\"Armstrong\">{{cite book | author=Armstrong, Duncan | title=\"Owd Padiham\" \u2013 a pictorial history | year=1985 | publisher=Mercer Print | location=Padiham  | isbn= | pages=}}</ref> The original churchyard did not extend as far to the north as it does today. In 1802 proposals were made to extend the churchyard and remove \"nuisances\" on the north side of the church. In 1835 the churchyard was extended northwards and it seems likely that at this time the former premises of Padiham Grammar School were purchased and demolished.<ref name = \"LCC Survey\"/>\n\nSherry's Lancashire Cotton Mill is a working 19th-century [[cotton mill]] which is open to the public.<ref>[http://www.visitburnley.com/things/MillShops.php Mill shops in Burnley and Padiham 2010] Accessed 21 October 2010</ref>\n\nPadiham Town Hall on Burnley Road, designed by [[Bradshaw Gass & Hope]] and built in 1938, is a Grade II listed building.<ref>[http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/libraries/librarydetails/libsearch1.asp?name=Padiham Lancashire County Council Library and Information Service] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419050141/http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/libraries/librarydetails/libsearch1.asp?name=Padiham |date=19 April 2008 }} Accessed 25 February 2008</ref>\n\nPadiham Memorial Park at the top of Church Street, was designed by [[Thomas Hayton Mawson|Thomas Mawson]], an influential and prolific landscape designer.<ref>[http://www.burnley.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=4&categoryID=200073&pageNumber=6 Burnley Borough Council report on restoration of Padiham Memorial Park] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615094826/http://www.burnley.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=4&categoryID=200073&pageNumber=6 |date=15 June 2011 }}. Accessed 28 July 2009</ref><ref name=\"Parks & Gardens UK\">[http://www.parksandgardens.ac.uk/component/option,com_parksandgardens/task,site/id,5378/Itemid,292/ Parks and Gardens register UK \u2013 the park had not been surveyed at the data accessed \u22123 February 2010] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311100335/http://www.parksandgardens.ac.uk/component/option,com_parksandgardens/task,site/id,5378/Itemid,292/ |date=11 March 2012 }}</ref><ref name = \"LGT\">[http://www.lancsgt.org.uk/ Lancashire Gardens Trust, accessed 17 April 2010]</ref> It was officially opened in 1921 as a memorial to those from the town who gave their lives in the [[First World War]], but it also records those who gave their lives in the Second World War.\n\nThe park covers {{convert|12|acre}} on two sites divided by the River Calder. The upper section is mainly formal, dominated by Knight Hill House, currently used as an [[Age UK]] (formerly [[Age Concern]]) day centre, and has a rose garden, lawns and two memorials. The lower section, off Park Street, has two bowling greens, tennis courts, skate park and Padiham Leisure Centre. The park is a [[Green Flag award]] winner.<ref>[http://www.greenflagaward.org.uk/winners/GSP001242/ Green Flag Award Scheme] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080207083526/http://www.greenflagaward.org.uk/winners/GSP001242/ |date=7 February 2008 }} Accessed 27 February 2008</ref> The park still had the remains of some Second World War [[air raid shelter]]s in 2008.<ref name=\"ARS\">{{cite web|title = World War II Air Raid shelters in Memorial Park|url = https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/755046|accessdate = 19 January 2009}}</ref>\n[[File:Padiham Old National School and Plaque.jpg|thumb|right|256px|The old [[National school (England and Wales)|National School]], Mill Street, built in 1830 and used until 1904]]\n\nPadiham War Memorial itself is at the main entrance to the park in Blackburn Road.<ref name=\"WWI\">{{cite web|title = World War I Cemeteries, Padiham War memorial (includes WWII)|url = http://www.ww1cemeteries.com/british_cemeteries_memorials/padiham_wm2.htm|accessdate = 19 January 2009|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081004203145/http://www.ww1cemeteries.com/british_cemeteries_memorials/padiham_wm2.htm|archivedate = 4 October 2008|df = dmy-all}}</ref> There is a second memorial at All Saints' with St John the Baptist off the A671, Padiham Road opposite the George IV pub.<ref name=\"WWISJ\">{{cite web|title = World War memorial at All Saints with St John the Baptist, BB12 6PA (includes WWII)|url = http://www.ww1cemeteries.com/british_cemeteries_memorials/padiham_stjohn_allsaints_wm.htm|accessdate = 19 January 2009|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081005032725/http://www.ww1cemeteries.com/british_cemeteries_memorials/padiham_stjohn_allsaints_wm.htm|archivedate = 5 October 2008|df = dmy-all}}</ref> A local man, Thomas Clayton, funded the park in his will; public subscription provided additional money for the park's many features.<ref>[http://www.burnley.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=4&pageNumber=5 Burnley Borough Council] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070914083209/http://www.burnley.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=4&pageNumber=5 |date=14 September 2007 }}. Accessed 28 February 2008.</ref>\n\nNear the war memorial, the Air Crash Memorial<ref name=\"ACM\">{{cite web|title = Air Crash Memorial, Padiham Memorial Park looking west in the direction of Blackburn|url = https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/755068|accessdate = 19 January 2009}}</ref> is a memorial to several young people from the town killed on 3 July 1970 when a [[Dan Air]] [[de Havilland Comet]] deviated from its intended course and crashed into the high ground of the [[Montseny Range]] in north-eastern Spain - see: [[Dan-Air Flight 1903]].\n\nThe aircraft, destroyed on impact and subsequent ground fire, contained three flight crew, four cabin crew and 105 passengers aboard, all of whom suffered fatal injuries. It was the airline's first fatal accident involving fare-paying passengers.<ref name=\"G-APDN\">{{cite web|title = Dan Air, air crash, northern Spain, Friday, 3 July 1970|url = http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19700703-0&lang=en|accessdate = 19 January 2009}}</ref> The tour operator, [[Clarksons Travel Group|Clarksons Holidays]], was at the time the largest [[package holiday]] company in Britain.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|title = BBC on this day, Friday, 3 July 1970|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/3/newsid_2492000/2492087.stm|accessdate = 19 January 2009 | date=3 July 1970|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nA number of other buildings in the area, less significant than Gawthorpe and others mentioned above, are still of historic interest. Hargrove can be seen from a public footpath off the Padiham by-pass and is just north of the town and the 1950s council housing estate north of Windermere Road. For over 400 years the house was the home of the Webster family of [[yeoman]] farmers.<ref name = \"Nadin&Armstrong\">{{Cite book |author1=Nadin, Jack |author2=Armstrong, Duncan | title=\"Padiham in Old Photographs\" \u2013 contains additional histories of properties mentioned| year=2009 | publisher=The History Press | isbn=978-0-7524-5188-6 | pages=10\u201316}}</ref> The house is probably 17th century and is part of the Huntroyed estate. Coal from a local [[outcrop]] heated the house for many years. Stockbridge House in Victoria Road was occupied by the Holts, a farming family, in 1802 and has a [[Jacobean architecture|Jacobean]] chimney.<ref name = \"Nadin&Armstrong\"/> High Whitaker Farm is north-east of Hargrove, also accessible by public footpath from both Higham Road and Grove Lane. The building is 16th century and said to have been used to [[English Reformation|hide Catholics]] during the reign of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]].<ref name = \"Nadin&Armstrong\"/> Other houses of note are Priddy Bank Farm and Foulds House Farm, both off Sabden Road, and [[Huntroyde Hall|Arbory Lodge]] on Arbory Drive.<ref name = \"Nadin&Armstrong\"/>\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Rail===\n\n[[Padiham railway station]] was on a branch line (usually known as the [[Great Harwood]] loop) of the [[East Lancashire Line]] from Burnley to [[Blackburn]] which opened in 1877; it was closed on 2 December 1957 and the railway station later demolished. The railway line was retained for continuing deliveries of coal to [[Padiham Power Station]] until the power station closed in 1993. The nearest railway station is now at [[Hapton railway station|Hapton]], about {{convert|2|mi|km|1}} south and the line converted to a footpath/bridleway/cycleway called the [[Padiham railway station#Greenway|Padiham Greenway]], completed in June 2010. The town is now served by [[Burnley Bus Company]] services from [[Accrington]], [[Burnley]], [[Nelson, Lancashire|Nelson]], [[Colne]] and beyond,<ref>[http://www.burnleyandpendle.co.uk/Ease/servlet/EaseFrameset?siteID=1472 Mainline bus services] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070822133053/http://www.burnleyandpendle.co.uk/Ease/servlet/EaseFrameset?siteID=1472 |date=22 August 2007 }}</ref> and [[Blackburn Bus Company]] service 152 from [[Burnley]], [[Blackburn]] and [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]].<ref>[http://www.lancashireunited.co.uk/ Lancashire United Bus Service]</ref>\n\n===Road===\n\nJunctions 8 and 10 of the [[M65 motorway|M65]], both around {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} from the town centre, give Padiham access to the motorway network. Junction 8 of the M65 also gives the town access to the [[A56 road|A56]] [[dual carriageway]] leading to the [[M66 motorway|M66]] and quick access to the [[Manchester]] motorway network.\n\nThe nearest airport, [[Manchester Airport|Manchester]], is 50 minutes' driving time from the town.<ref>[http://www.theaa.com/travelwatch/inc/planner_places_redirect.jsp www.theaa.com The AA route planning. Accessed 8 February 2010]</ref> The most convenient route by public transport \u2013 via Blackburn, then by train \u2013 takes approx. 2\u00bc hours.<ref>[http://www.transportdirect.info/Web2/JourneyPlanning/JourneyPlannerInput.aspx Journey planner direct website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613090736/http://www.transportdirect.info/Web2/JourneyPlanning/JourneyPlannerInput.aspx |date=13 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Flooding==\n\nIn December 2015, central Padiham was severely damaged by flooding when the River Calder burst its banks and engulfed neighbouring homes and businesses. Restoration work continues.\n\n==Historic maps==\nThe 1845<ref name = \"LCC Survey\"/><ref name=\"OS Map 1845\">[http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/environment/oldmap/os1845/padiham/padiham.gif Detailed version of map at the Lancashire County Council website]</ref> map (1) shows the town of Padiham in the early days of the Lancashire [[Cotton Mill|cotton industry]] in [[Victorian era|Victorian times]] with three mills already marked. Most of the town at this stage was north of the river. Part of the [[Huntroyde Hall|Huntroyde Demesne]]<ref name=\"Hunt\"/> is marked in the top left corner. The [[River Calder, Lancashire|River Calder]], on the right of the map, flows to the north, having been diverted from its original route, away from Gawthorpe Hall (indicated in pink), in the early 19th century, because of pollution. In the 1960s the river was re-routed to its original course to accommodate [[open cast mining|open cast coal mining]].<ref name=\"Armstrong\"/>\nThe 1890 [[Ordnance Survey]] map (2) shows the growth of the cotton industry in the latter part of the 19th century. \nThe 1\u201325,000 scale OS map (3) is a partial extract from the two maps indicated. A number of historical locations are shown including [[Read, Lancashire|Read Hall]] (A2) and [[Read, Lancashire|Read]] (B2); Martholme, just east of the start of the [[Martholme Viaduct]] (A3); [[Simonstone, Lancashire|Simonstone]] and Simonstone Hall (C3); [[Huntroyde Hall|Huntroyd]] and grounds (D1-D2); [[Padiham Power Station]] (D3) with the connecting branch line for fuel; post-war housing development north of the town off Slade Lane (E2); High Whitaker (F1); River Calder on the old alignment from Gawthore Hall and grounds (F2); Location of [[Pendle Hall]] (G1); Location of [[Ightenhill]] Manor House (G2); [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]] in Burnley (J1). The line of the railway line through Padiham is also shown.\n<gallery widths=\"260px\" heights=\"260px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Padiham map ca1844.jpg|1: Map of Padiham c.&nbsp;1844\n\nFile:Padiham OS map 1890.jpg|2: Ordnance Survey map dated 1890\n\nFile:OS Map extract SD73+SD83.jpg|3: Extract from OS 1-25,000 scale maps SD73 (west section pub 1955) and SD83 (east section published 1954) showing historical locations around Padiham. Grid lines are 1&nbsp;km.\n</gallery>\n\n==Notable people==\n<!----Please use alphabetical order----->\n*[[William Blezard]] (1921\u20132003), composer born in Padiham, who worked with [[Joyce Grenfell]] and others\n*[[Thomas Birtwistle]] (1833\u20131912), trade unionist involved in the weavers' strikes at Padiham in 1859\n*[[Richard Bradshaw (footballer)|Richard Bradshaw]] (fl. 1900s) footballer born in Padiham, played for [[Blackpool F.C.]]\n*[[Maurice Green (journalist)|Maurice Green]] (1906\u20131987), editor of ''[[The Financial Times]]'' and ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' born in Padiham\n*[[Sir Cyril Ernest Harrison|Cyril Harrison]] (1901\u20131980), managing director of [[English Sewing Cotton Company]], educated at Padiham [[Weslyan]] School\n*[[Wayne Hemingway|Gerardine Hemingway [[MBE]] (living), fashion designer, wife and business partner of [[Wayne Hemingway]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hemingwaydesign.co.uk/teams/2 |title=Hemingway Design \u2013 Meet the team |publisher=Hemingway Design |accessdate=1 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809063330/http://www.hemingwaydesign.co.uk/teams/2 |archivedate=9 August 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*[[Harry Hill (cyclist)|Harry Hill]] (1916\u20132009), Padiham-born cyclist, [[bronze medal]]list at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]] in [[Berlin]].<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/hi/harry-hill-1.html Sports Reference, accessed 28 September 2010]</ref> Too poor to get to London any other way, Hill cycled the 200 miles from [[Sheffield]] on the bike he used in the Olympic Games.<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{cite news|title = Goodbye to a true cycling superstar|work = Radcliffe|publisher = Bury Times|date = 5 February 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Sir James Kay-Shuttleworth, 1st Baronet]] (1804\u20131877), husband of Janet Kay-Shuttleworth of Gawthorpe Hall, founded [[Teacher education|teacher training]] and independent school inspection in England and what has become the [[University of St Mark & St John]], known as \"Marjon\".\n*[[Ughtred James Kay-Shuttleworth]] (1844\u20131939), 1st Baron Shuttleworth, Liberal politician, son of Sir James Kay-Shuttleworth. [[Under-Secretary of State for India]] and [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]] under [[William Ewart Gladstone|William Gladstone]] in 1886 and [[Parliamentary and Financial Secretary to the Admiralty]] under Gladstone and [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|Lord Rosebery]] in 1892\u20131895. He inherited Gawthorpe on his mother's death in 1872.\n*[[Charles Kay-Shuttleworth, 5th Baron Shuttleworth]] (born 1948), [[Lord Lieutenant of Lancashire]] in 1997\n*[[John Pierce Chamberlain Starkie]] (1830\u20131888), landowner at [[Ashton Hall]], in [[Thurnham, Lancashire]]\n*[[Le Gendre Starkie (1799\u20131865)]] and [[Le Gendre Starkie (1828\u20131899)]], landowners at Huntroyde\n*[[Alfred Tysoe]] (1874\u20131901), Padiham-born athlete and winner of two [[gold medal]]s in the 800m and 5,000m team races in the [[1900 Summer Olympics|1900 Olympic Games]]<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ty/alfred-tysoe-1.html Sports Reference website, accessed 28 September 2010]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Listed buildings in Padiham]]\n* [[History of Lancashire]]\n* The [[Bront\u00eb Way]]\n* [[Lancashire Cotton Corporation]]: set up to rescue the cotton industry from 1929\n* [[Lancashire Cotton Famine]]: the impact of the [[American Civil War]] on the cotton industry in north-west England by problems with US cotton imports\n* [[List of mills in Lancashire#Padiham|List of mills in Padiham]]\n* [[Burnley Corporation Tramways]]\n* [[List of schools in Burnley|List of schools in the Borough of Burnley]]\n* [[Leck Hall]]: current seat of [[Baron Shuttleworth]], of [[Gawthorpe Hall]]\n* [[Padiham F.C.]] The town's football club founded 1878\n* [http://www.burnley.gov.uk/sites/default/files/____Padiham_Appraisal_Final_LowRes.pdf Padiham Heritage Appraisal 2015]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Padiham}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071126011055/http://www.burnley.gov.uk/site/index.php Burnley Borough Council]\n*[http://www.padihamparish.org/ Church of England Parish of Padiham and Hapton]\n*[http://www.padihamtowncouncil.gov.uk/ Padiham Town Council]\n*[http://www.visitburnley.com/padiham.php Visit Padiham]\n*[http://archivecat.lancashire.gov.uk/CalmView/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=UDPA&pos=1 Padiham Urban District Council archive catalogue]\n*{{oscoor gbx|SD7933}}\n\n{{Borough of Burnley}}\n{{Lancashire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Padiham| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Districts in Burnley]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:History of Lancashire]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|static_image_name=         Padiham Town Hall.jpg\n|static_image_caption=      Padiham Town Hall in 1994,<br />designed by [[Bradshaw Gass & Hope]] 1938\n| official_name=            Padiham\n| country=                  England\n| region=                   North West England\n| area_total_sq_mi=         {{convert|636.11|ha|mi2|2|disp=number}}\n| area_footnotes=           <ref name=pop/>\n| population=               10,098\n| population_ref=           ''(2011)'' <ref name=pop/>\n| os_grid_reference=        SD7933\n| coordinates=              {{coord|53.797|-2.311|display=inline,title}}\n| post_town=                BURNLEY\n| postcode_area=            BB\n| postcode_district=        BB12\n| dial_code=                01282\n| civil_parish=             Padiham\n| shire_district=           [[Burnley (borough)|Burnley]]\n| shire_county=             [[Lancashire]]\n| constituency_westminster= [[Burnley (UK Parliament constituency)|Burnley]]\n| pushpin_map=              United Kingdom Borough of Burnley\n| pushpin_map_caption=      Shown within Burnley Borough\n}}\n\n<!----------IMAGES--------->\n[[File:Church Street Padiham.jpg|thumb|right|256px|Church Street looking north from St Leonard's, c.&nbsp;1900. The Old Black Bull is next to the church. The view has hardly changed, but unlike some others, the street is no longer [[cobblestones|cobbled]].]]\n[[File:St Leonard's Church, Padiham, from Guy Street.jpg|thumb|right|256px|St Leonard's Church, from Guy Street]]\n[[File:Gawthorpe new.jpg|thumb|right|256px|[[Gawthorpe Hall]] in Padiham. Owned by\n[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] but jointly managed with [[Lancashire County Council]].]]\n<!----------IMAGES END----->\n\n'''Padiham''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|\u00e6|d|i|\u0259|m}} {{respell|PAD|i|\u0259m}}) is a small town and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] on the [[River Calder, Lancashire|River Calder]], about {{convert|3|mi|km|0|spell=in}} west of [[Burnley]] and south of [[Pendle Hill]], in [[Lancashire, England|Lancashire]], England. It is part of the [[Burnley (borough)|Borough of Burnley]], but has its own [[Town Council#United Kingdom|town council]] with varied powers. Padiham was originally a rural village lying by the River Calder. It is still surrounded by attractive countryside on an arc running from the north-west to the north-east in the foothills of Pendle Hill.\n\nAccording to the [[United Kingdom Census 2011]], the parish has a population of 10,098,<ref name=pop>{{NOMIS2011|id=1170214988|title=Padiham Parish|accessdate=8 February 2018}}\n</ref> an increase from 8,998 in the 2001 census.<ref>[http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790436 Office for National Statistics : ''Census 2001 : Parish Headcounts : Burnley''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202328/http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790436 |date=3 March 2016 }} Retrieved 4 February 2010</ref>\n\n==History==\nNo prehistoric or [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] sites have been found in the urban area and Padiham, a name of [[Anglo-Saxon]] origin, is not recorded in the [[Domesday Book]].<ref name=\"LCC Survey\">[http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/environment/documents/historictowns/PadihamComplete_LowRes.pdf Historic Town Assessment Report, Padiham, Lancashire County Council, May 2005, includes several old maps of the town and location of buildings \u2013 accessed 18 August 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001080455/http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/environment/documents/historictowns/PadihamComplete_LowRes.pdf |date=1 October 2012 }}</ref> The first recorded mention of the town, as ''Padyngham'', dates from 1294.<ref>[http://www.visitburnley.com/padiham.php About Padiham Accessed 4 February 2010]</ref> For hundreds of years it was a market town where produce from [[Pendle Hill|Pendleside]] was bought and sold. The town expanded and was substantially redeveloped during the [[Industrial Revolution]] and the central area is now a [[conservation area]].\n\nPadiham's population peaked around 1921 at about 14,000 declining to 10,000 in the early 1960s and 8,998 at the time of the 2001 census.<ref name=VoB/><ref>[http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=795670&c=padiham&d=16&e=15&g=461314&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1197124485873&enc=1&dsFamilyId=779 2001 census data]. Accessed 8 December 2007</ref> This follows people moving to the south of England in search of work following the decline of the traditional cotton, coal and engineering manufacturing base during that period.\n\nThe [[Queen Elizabeth II|Queen]], together with [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]], first visited [[Burnley]], [[Nelson, Lancashire|Nelson]] and the old [[Mullard]] valve factory at [[Simonstone, Lancashire|Simonstone]] near Padiham on her post-[[Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II|Coronation]] tour of Lancashire in 1955.<ref name = \"Pathe\">[http://www.britishpathe.com/video/royal-tour-of-lancashire-1/query/Queen+Elizabeth+Burnley British Path\u00e9 Newsreel 1995 Accessed 2014_02_01]</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nPadiham was once a [[Township (England)|township]] in the ancient parish of Whalley. This became a [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in 1866.<ref name=VoB>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit/10375502/relationships|title=Padiham Ch/CP through time|publisher=GB Historical GIS / University of Portsmouth|work=visionofbritain.org.uk|accessdate=18 October 2013}}</ref> An [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]] covered the town from 1894 (until 1974), however at this time the rural areas mainly to the north became a new civil parish called Northtown, forming part of the [[Burnley Rural District]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit/10374121/relationships|title=Northtown CP through time|publisher=GB Historical GIS / University of Portsmouth|work=visionofbritain.org.uk|accessdate=18 October 2013}}</ref> But the Padiham Green area, previously part of Hapton,{{efn|name=Hapton|The old township boundary with [[Hapton, Lancashire|Hapton]] followed the [[River Calder, Lancashire|River Calder]] and its tributary [[Green Brook, Lancashire|Green Brook]].<ref name=OS>{{Cite map |publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]] |title=Lancashire and Furness |series=County Series |scale=1 : 10,560 |edition=1st |year=1848}}</ref>}} transferred to Padiham with another small area following in 1935.<ref name=VoB/> Since 1974 Padiham has formed part of the [[Borough of Burnley]]. A [[Town Council]] was established in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.padihamtowncouncil.gov.uk/html/about_us.html|title=Padiham Town Council \u2013 About us|accessdate=13 October 2013|publisher=Padiham Town Council|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019141521/http://www.padihamtowncouncil.gov.uk/html/about_us.html|archivedate=19 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCouncillors for Padiham on [[Borough of Burnley|Burnley Borough Council]] are elected to the [[Gawthorpe Ward]], which covers most of Padiham but not [[Gawthorpe Hall]],<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Ordnance Survey |title=Gawthorpe |website=Ordnance Survey Linked Data Platform |url=http://data.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/doc/7000000000004603 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> with the southern and eastern areas covered by the Hapton with Park Ward.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Ordnance Survey |title=Hapton with Park |website=Ordnance Survey Linked Data Platform |url=http://data.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/doc/7000000000004619 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> Burnley Borough Council now addresses public correspondence to both the people of Burnley and Padiham. Padiham is part of [[Lancashire County Council]] and the Parliamentary Constituency is [[Burnley (UK Parliament constituency)|Burnley]] currently represented by [[Antony Higginbotham]] for the Conservative Party.\n\n==Economy==\nIn the 19th century, Padiham's industry was based on [[coal-mining]] and [[Mill town|weaving]]. Helm Mill on Factory Lane was the first mill built in 1807. By 1906 there were twenty [[cotton mill]]s<ref name = \"Pevsner\">{{cite book | author=Pevsner, Nikolaus; Hartwell, Clare (revision)| title=The Buildings of England \u2013 Lancashire: North| year=2009 | publisher=Yale University Press | location=London and New Haven | isbn=978-0-300-12667-9 | pages=490\u2013496}}</ref> though the best preserved, now converted into flats, is Victoria Mill, built 1852\u201353 with an 1873 extension, in Ightenhill Street.<ref name = \"Pevsner\"/>  Many local cotton workers were members of the [[Padiham Weavers' Association]], the membership of which peaked in 1907 at more than 6,000.<ref name=\"marsh\">{{cite book|last1=Marsh|first1=Arthur|last2=Ryan|first2=Victoria|last3=Smethurst|first3=John B.|title=Historical Directory of Trade Unions|volume=4|date=1994|publisher=Ashgate|location=Farnham|isbn=9780859679008|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historicaldirect0004mars/page/114 114]|url=https://archive.org/details/historicaldirect0004mars/page/114}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Report on Trade Unions in 1905-1907|date=1909|publisher=Board of Trade|location=London|pages=82\u2013101}}</ref>\n\nIndustrial development was helped by the proximity of the [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]] about {{convert|2|mi|km|1}} south. By 1848, Padiham had many coal pits around the town, including two large collieries and a number of smaller workings. The availability of coal and water nearby helped the development of the cotton industry in the town.<ref name = \"LCC Survey\"/> The arrival of the railway at [[Hapton, Lancashire|Hapton]] in 1840 and Padiham itself in 1877 further boosted industry in the town.<ref name = \"LCC Survey\"/> The last pit closed around 1870,<ref>[http://www.padihamlife.co.uk/about/mining.htm Padiham Life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828155231/http://www.padihamlife.co.uk/about/mining.htm |date=28 August 2008 }}</ref> although mining continued in areas outside the town into the 1950s and [[open cast mining]] took place in the 1960s east of the town close to Gawthorpe Hall but north of the River Calder off Grove Lane.\n\nSince the 1960s the remaining cotton mills have also continued a decline which began in the 1930s. Padiham's second role as a manufacturing base has also been in decline since the 1990s. The town's last major employer in this sector, [[Baxi]], closed its factory in March 2007 with the loss of 500 jobs.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/lancashire/6453773.stm '' 'Job Threat After Factory Closure' '', BBC News website 15 March 2007, accessed 14 January 2008]</ref> A modern business park, ''Shuttleworth Mead'',<ref>[http://www.ribbleindustrialestatesltd.co.uk/ Shuttleworth Mead Business Park]. Accessed 5 September 2008</ref> opened in 2001 on the western edge of the town on the site of the old [[Padiham Power Station]]<ref>[http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/corporate/web/?REMADE/20211 Lancashire County Council proposals for public footpath July 2009, Accessed 11 February 2010] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120804143825/http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/corporate/web/?REMADE/20211 |date=4 August 2012 }}</ref> which closed in 1993, supported by \u00a32.2&nbsp;million from the [[European Regional Development Fund]] and \u00a32&nbsp;million from the [[Regional Development Agency|North West Development Agency]].<ref>[http://nwda.co.uk/ North West Regional Development Agency]. Accessed 6 September 2008</ref> Tenants include Supanet, an internet service provider ([[ISP]]) and Graham & Brown, a wallcoverings company.\n\nIn 2007 Fort Vale Engineering moved into the old [[Mullard]]/Philips site at Calder Vale Park, [[Simonstone, Lancashire|Simonstone]] which had closed in 2004, and developed a new purpose-built factory. Fort Vale Engineering employs around 280 people from around the local area and has brought new business to other local employers.\n\n==Landmarks==\n\nThere are five significant halls in the local area: [[Huntroyde Hall]],<ref name=\"Hunt\">[http://www.parksandgardens.ac.uk/component/option,com_parksandgardens/task,site/id,5227/Itemid,292/ Parks and Gardens UK \u2013 based on the English Heritage Register of Parks and Gardens of Special Historic Interest] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226091547/http://www.parksandgardens.ac.uk/component/option,com_parksandgardens/task,site/id,5227/Itemid,292/ |date=26 February 2012 }}</ref> dating from 1576, and [[Simonstone, Lancashire#Simonstone Hall|Simonstone Hall]], dating from 1660, in nearby [[Simonstone, Lancashire|Simonstone]], are both privately owned. [[Gawthorpe Hall]] was donated to the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] in 1970 but is jointly managed with [[Lancashire County Council]], which has a 99-year lease. Gawthorpe is in the [[Ightenhill]] district.<ref>[http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-gawthorpehall National Trust Website, accessed 2 October 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080921232519/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-gawthorpehall |date=21 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe Trust also runs an office and a tea room in the courtyard of the property.<ref>[http://www.r-alston.co.uk/ch_eng.htm Searchable guide to country houses, includes Gawthorpe and other houses owned by the Shuttleworths \u2013 accessed 18 April 2010] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040204052356/http://www.r-alston.co.uk/ch_eng.htm |date=4 February 2004 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Padiham/ www.genuki.org.uk] Accessed 13 November 2007</ref> Gawthorpe was the family home of the Shuttleworth family who occupied [[Shuttleworth Hall]] near Hapton from the 12th century.<ref>[http://www.grimshaworigin.org/WebPages/ShutGawt.htm Grimshaw and Shuttleworth family origin website, accessed 15 January 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228171757/http://www.grimshaworigin.org/WebPages/ShutGawt.htm |date=28 December 2012 }}</ref><ref name = \"Pevsner2\">{{Cite book | author=Pevsner, Nikolaus; Hartwell, Clare (revision)| title=The Buildings of England \u2013 Lancashire: North| year=2009 | publisher=Yale University Press | location=London and New Haven | isbn=978-0-300-12667-9 | page=321}}</ref> The current building dates from 1639 and is still a working farm. [[Read Hall and Park]] is in the nearby village of [[Read, Lancashire|Read]], about {{convert|1|mi|km|1}} west of Padiham on the [[A671 road|A671]].\n\n[[File:St Matthews Padiham 2007-12-12.jpg|thumb|right|256px|St Leonard's Parish Church]]\nSt Leonard's Church, the town's parish church, dates from 1866\u201369 and is a [[Grade II listed building]].<ref>[http://lfhhs-pendleandburnley.org.uk/church/xpad1.htm Lancashire Family History & Heraldry Society]. Accessed 13 November 2007</ref> It was built on the site of earlier churches dating back to at least 1451.<ref name=\"Armstrong\">{{cite book | author=Armstrong, Duncan | title=\"Owd Padiham\" \u2013 a pictorial history | year=1985 | publisher=Mercer Print | location=Padiham  | isbn= | pages=}}</ref> The original churchyard did not extend as far to the north as it does today. In 1802 proposals were made to extend the churchyard and remove \"nuisances\" on the north side of the church. In 1835 the churchyard was extended northwards and it seems likely that at this time the former premises of Padiham Grammar School were purchased and demolished.<ref name = \"LCC Survey\"/>\n\nSherry's Lancashire Cotton Mill is a working 19th-century [[cotton mill]] which is open to the public.<ref>[http://www.visitburnley.com/things/MillShops.php Mill shops in Burnley and Padiham 2010] Accessed 21 October 2010</ref>\n\nPadiham Town Hall on Burnley Road, designed by [[Bradshaw Gass & Hope]] and built in 1938, is a Grade II listed building.<ref>[http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/libraries/librarydetails/libsearch1.asp?name=Padiham Lancashire County Council Library and Information Service] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419050141/http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/libraries/librarydetails/libsearch1.asp?name=Padiham |date=19 April 2008 }} Accessed 25 February 2008</ref>\n\nPadiham Memorial Park at the top of Church Street, was designed by [[Thomas Hayton Mawson|Thomas Mawson]], an influential and prolific landscape designer.<ref>[http://www.burnley.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=4&categoryID=200073&pageNumber=6 Burnley Borough Council report on restoration of Padiham Memorial Park] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615094826/http://www.burnley.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=4&categoryID=200073&pageNumber=6 |date=15 June 2011 }}. Accessed 28 July 2009</ref><ref name=\"Parks & Gardens UK\">[http://www.parksandgardens.ac.uk/component/option,com_parksandgardens/task,site/id,5378/Itemid,292/ Parks and Gardens register UK \u2013 the park had not been surveyed at the data accessed \u22123 February 2010] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311100335/http://www.parksandgardens.ac.uk/component/option,com_parksandgardens/task,site/id,5378/Itemid,292/ |date=11 March 2012 }}</ref><ref name = \"LGT\">[http://www.lancsgt.org.uk/ Lancashire Gardens Trust, accessed 17 April 2010]</ref> It was officially opened in 1921 as a memorial to those from the town who gave their lives in the [[First World War]], but it also records those who gave their lives in the Second World War.\n\nThe park covers {{convert|12|acre}} on two sites divided by the River Calder. The upper section is mainly formal, dominated by Knight Hill House, currently used as an [[Age UK]] (formerly [[Age Concern]]) day centre, and has a rose garden, lawns and two memorials. The lower section, off Park Street, has two bowling greens, tennis courts, skate park and Padiham Leisure Centre. The park is a [[Green Flag award]] winner.<ref>[http://www.greenflagaward.org.uk/winners/GSP001242/ Green Flag Award Scheme] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080207083526/http://www.greenflagaward.org.uk/winners/GSP001242/ |date=7 February 2008 }} Accessed 27 February 2008</ref> The park still had the remains of some Second World War [[air raid shelter]]s in 2008.<ref name=\"ARS\">{{cite web|title = World War II Air Raid shelters in Memorial Park|url = https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/755046|accessdate = 19 January 2009}}</ref>\n[[File:Padiham Old National School and Plaque.jpg|thumb|right|256px|The old [[National school (England and Wales)|National School]], Mill Street, built in 1830 and used until 1904]]\n\nPadiham War Memorial itself is at the main entrance to the park in Blackburn Road.<ref name=\"WWI\">{{cite web|title = World War I Cemeteries, Padiham War memorial (includes WWII)|url = http://www.ww1cemeteries.com/british_cemeteries_memorials/padiham_wm2.htm|accessdate = 19 January 2009|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081004203145/http://www.ww1cemeteries.com/british_cemeteries_memorials/padiham_wm2.htm|archivedate = 4 October 2008|df = dmy-all}}</ref> There is a second memorial at All Saints' with St John the Baptist off the A671, Padiham Road opposite the George IV pub.<ref name=\"WWISJ\">{{cite web|title = World War memorial at All Saints with St John the Baptist, BB12 6PA (includes WWII)|url = http://www.ww1cemeteries.com/british_cemeteries_memorials/padiham_stjohn_allsaints_wm.htm|accessdate = 19 January 2009|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081005032725/http://www.ww1cemeteries.com/british_cemeteries_memorials/padiham_stjohn_allsaints_wm.htm|archivedate = 5 October 2008|df = dmy-all}}</ref> A local man, Thomas Clayton, funded the park in his will; public subscription provided additional money for the park's many features.<ref>[http://www.burnley.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=4&pageNumber=5 Burnley Borough Council] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070914083209/http://www.burnley.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=4&pageNumber=5 |date=14 September 2007 }}. Accessed 28 February 2008.</ref>\n\nNear the war memorial, the Air Crash Memorial<ref name=\"ACM\">{{cite web|title = Air Crash Memorial, Padiham Memorial Park looking west in the direction of Blackburn|url = https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/755068|accessdate = 19 January 2009}}</ref> is a memorial to several young people from the town killed on 3 July 1970 when a [[Dan Air]] [[de Havilland Comet]] deviated from its intended course and crashed into the high ground of the [[Montseny Range]] in north-eastern Spain - see: [[Dan-Air Flight 1903]].\n\nThe aircraft, destroyed on impact and subsequent ground fire, contained three flight crew, four cabin crew and 105 passengers aboard, all of whom suffered fatal injuries. It was the airline's first fatal accident involving fare-paying passengers.<ref name=\"G-APDN\">{{cite web|title = Dan Air, air crash, northern Spain, Friday, 3 July 1970|url = http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19700703-0&lang=en|accessdate = 19 January 2009}}</ref> The tour operator, [[Clarksons Travel Group|Clarksons Holidays]], was at the time the largest [[package holiday]] company in Britain.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|title = BBC on this day, Friday, 3 July 1970|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/3/newsid_2492000/2492087.stm|accessdate = 19 January 2009 | date=3 July 1970|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nA number of other buildings in the area, less significant than Gawthorpe and others mentioned above, are still of historic interest. Hargrove can be seen from a public footpath off the Padiham by-pass and is just north of the town and the 1950s council housing estate north of Windermere Road. For over 400 years the house was the home of the Webster family of [[yeoman]] farmers.<ref name = \"Nadin&Armstrong\">{{Cite book |author1=Nadin, Jack |author2=Armstrong, Duncan | title=\"Padiham in Old Photographs\" \u2013 contains additional histories of properties mentioned| year=2009 | publisher=The History Press | isbn=978-0-7524-5188-6 | pages=10\u201316}}</ref> The house is probably 17th century and is part of the Huntroyed estate. Coal from a local [[outcrop]] heated the house for many years. Stockbridge House in Victoria Road was occupied by the Holts, a farming family, in 1802 and has a [[Jacobean architecture|Jacobean]] chimney.<ref name = \"Nadin&Armstrong\"/> High Whitaker Farm is north-east of Hargrove, also accessible by public footpath from both Higham Road and Grove Lane. The building is 16th century and said to have been used to [[English Reformation|hide Catholics]] during the reign of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]].<ref name = \"Nadin&Armstrong\"/> Other houses of note are Priddy Bank Farm and Foulds House Farm, both off Sabden Road, and [[Huntroyde Hall|Arbory Lodge]] on Arbory Drive.<ref name = \"Nadin&Armstrong\"/>\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Rail===\n\n[[Padiham railway station]] was on a branch line (usually known as the [[Great Harwood]] loop) of the [[East Lancashire Line]] from Burnley to [[Blackburn]] which opened in 1877; it was closed on 2 December 1957 and the railway station later demolished. The railway line was retained for continuing deliveries of coal to [[Padiham Power Station]] until the power station closed in 1993. The nearest railway station is now at [[Hapton railway station|Hapton]], about {{convert|2|mi|km|1}} south and the line converted to a footpath/bridleway/cycleway called the [[Padiham railway station#Greenway|Padiham Greenway]], completed in June 2010. The town is now served by [[Burnley Bus Company]] services from [[Accrington]], [[Burnley]], [[Nelson, Lancashire|Nelson]], [[Colne]] and beyond,<ref>[http://www.burnleyandpendle.co.uk/Ease/servlet/EaseFrameset?siteID=1472 Mainline bus services] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070822133053/http://www.burnleyandpendle.co.uk/Ease/servlet/EaseFrameset?siteID=1472 |date=22 August 2007 }}</ref> and [[Blackburn Bus Company]] service 152 from [[Burnley]], [[Blackburn]] and [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]].<ref>[http://www.lancashireunited.co.uk/ Lancashire United Bus Service]</ref>\n\n===Road===\n\nJunctions 8 and 10 of the [[M65 motorway|M65]], both around {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} from the town centre, give Padiham access to the motorway network. Junction 8 of the M65 also gives the town access to the [[A56 road|A56]] [[dual carriageway]] leading to the [[M66 motorway|M66]] and quick access to the [[Manchester]] motorway network.\n\nThe nearest airport, [[Manchester Airport|Manchester]], is 50 minutes' driving time from the town.<ref>[http://www.theaa.com/travelwatch/inc/planner_places_redirect.jsp www.theaa.com The AA route planning. Accessed 8 February 2010]</ref> The most convenient route by public transport \u2013 via Blackburn, then by train \u2013 takes approx. 2\u00bc hours.<ref>[http://www.transportdirect.info/Web2/JourneyPlanning/JourneyPlannerInput.aspx Journey planner direct website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613090736/http://www.transportdirect.info/Web2/JourneyPlanning/JourneyPlannerInput.aspx |date=13 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Flooding==\n\nIn December 2015, central Padiham was severely damaged by flooding when the River Calder burst its banks and engulfed neighbouring homes and businesses. Restoration work continues.\n\n==Historic maps==\nThe 1845<ref name = \"LCC Survey\"/><ref name=\"OS Map 1845\">[http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/environment/oldmap/os1845/padiham/padiham.gif Detailed version of map at the Lancashire County Council website]</ref> map (1) shows the town of Padiham in the early days of the Lancashire [[Cotton Mill|cotton industry]] in [[Victorian era|Victorian times]] with three mills already marked. Most of the town at this stage was north of the river. Part of the [[Huntroyde Hall|Huntroyde Demesne]]<ref name=\"Hunt\"/> is marked in the top left corner. The [[River Calder, Lancashire|River Calder]], on the right of the map, flows to the north, having been diverted from its original route, away from Gawthorpe Hall (indicated in pink), in the early 19th century, because of pollution. In the 1960s the river was re-routed to its original course to accommodate [[open cast mining|open cast coal mining]].<ref name=\"Armstrong\"/>\nThe 1890 [[Ordnance Survey]] map (2) shows the growth of the cotton industry in the latter part of the 19th century. \nThe 1\u201325,000 scale OS map (3) is a partial extract from the two maps indicated. A number of historical locations are shown including [[Read, Lancashire|Read Hall]] (A2) and [[Read, Lancashire|Read]] (B2); Martholme, just east of the start of the [[Martholme Viaduct]] (A3); [[Simonstone, Lancashire|Simonstone]] and Simonstone Hall (C3); [[Huntroyde Hall|Huntroyd]] and grounds (D1-D2); [[Padiham Power Station]] (D3) with the connecting branch line for fuel; post-war housing development north of the town off Slade Lane (E2); High Whitaker (F1); River Calder on the old alignment from Gawthore Hall and grounds (F2); Location of [[Pendle Hall]] (G1); Location of [[Ightenhill]] Manor House (G2); [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]] in Burnley (J1). The line of the railway line through Padiham is also shown.\n<gallery widths=\"260px\" heights=\"260px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Padiham map ca1844.jpg|1: Map of Padiham c.&nbsp;1844\n\nFile:Padiham OS map 1890.jpg|2: Ordnance Survey map dated 1890\n\nFile:OS Map extract SD73+SD83.jpg|3: Extract from OS 1-25,000 scale maps SD73 (west section pub 1955) and SD83 (east section published 1954) showing historical locations around Padiham. Grid lines are 1&nbsp;km.\n</gallery>\n\n==People==\n<!----Please use alphabetical order----->\n*[[William Blezard]] (1921\u20132003), composer born in Padiham, who worked with [[Joyce Grenfell]] and others\n*[[Thomas Birtwistle]] (1833\u20131912), trade unionist involved in the weavers' strikes at Padiham in 1859\n*[[Richard Bradshaw (footballer)|Richard Bradshaw]] (fl. 1900s) footballer born in Padiham, played for [[Blackpool F.C.]]\n*[[Maurice Green (journalist)|Maurice Green]] (1906\u20131987), editor of ''[[The Financial Times]]'' and ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' born in Padiham\n*[[Sir Cyril Ernest Harrison|Cyril Harrison]] (1901\u20131980), managing director of [[English Sewing Cotton Company]], educated at Padiham [[Weslyan]] School\n*[[Wayne Hemingway|Gerardine Hemingway [[MBE]] (living), fashion designer, wife and business partner of [[Wayne Hemingway]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hemingwaydesign.co.uk/teams/2 |title=Hemingway Design \u2013 Meet the team |publisher=Hemingway Design |accessdate=1 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809063330/http://www.hemingwaydesign.co.uk/teams/2 |archivedate=9 August 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*[[Harry Hill (cyclist)|Harry Hill]] (1916\u20132009), Padiham-born cyclist, [[bronze medal]]list at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]] in [[Berlin]].<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/hi/harry-hill-1.html Sports Reference, accessed 28 September 2010]</ref> Too poor to get to London any other way, Hill cycled the 200 miles from [[Sheffield]] on the bike he used in the Olympic Games.<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{cite news|title = Goodbye to a true cycling superstar|work = Radcliffe|publisher = Bury Times|date = 5 February 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Sir James Kay-Shuttleworth, 1st Baronet]] (1804\u20131877), husband of Janet Kay-Shuttleworth of Gawthorpe Hall, founded [[Teacher education|teacher training]] and independent school inspection in England and what has become the [[University of St Mark & St John]], known as \"Marjon\".\n*[[Ughtred James Kay-Shuttleworth]] (1844\u20131939), 1st Baron Shuttleworth, Liberal politician, son of Sir James Kay-Shuttleworth. [[Under-Secretary of State for India]] and [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]] under [[William Ewart Gladstone|William Gladstone]] in 1886 and [[Parliamentary and Financial Secretary to the Admiralty]] under Gladstone and [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|Lord Rosebery]] in 1892\u20131895. He inherited Gawthorpe on his mother's death in 1872.\n*[[Charles Kay-Shuttleworth, 5th Baron Shuttleworth]] (born 1948), [[Lord Lieutenant of Lancashire]] in 1997\n*[[John Pierce Chamberlain Starkie]] (1830\u20131888), landowner at [[Ashton Hall]], in [[Thurnham, Lancashire]]\n*[[Le Gendre Starkie (1799\u20131865)]] and [[Le Gendre Starkie (1828\u20131899)]], landowners at Huntroyde\n*[[Alfred Tysoe]] (1874\u20131901), Padiham-born athlete and winner of two [[gold medal]]s in the 800m and 5,000m team races in the [[1900 Summer Olympics|1900 Olympic Games]]<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ty/alfred-tysoe-1.html Sports Reference website, accessed 28 September 2010]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Listed buildings in Padiham]]\n* [[History of Lancashire]]\n* The [[Bront\u00eb Way]]\n* [[Lancashire Cotton Corporation]]: set up to rescue the cotton industry from 1929\n* [[Lancashire Cotton Famine]]: the impact of the [[American Civil War]] on the cotton industry in north-west England by problems with US cotton imports\n* [[List of mills in Lancashire#Padiham|List of mills in Padiham]]\n* [[Burnley Corporation Tramways]]\n* [[List of schools in Burnley|List of schools in the Borough of Burnley]]\n* [[Leck Hall]]: current seat of [[Baron Shuttleworth]], of [[Gawthorpe Hall]]\n* [[Padiham F.C.]] The town's football club founded 1878\n* [http://www.burnley.gov.uk/sites/default/files/____Padiham_Appraisal_Final_LowRes.pdf Padiham Heritage Appraisal 2015]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Padiham}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071126011055/http://www.burnley.gov.uk/site/index.php Burnley Borough Council]\n*[http://www.padihamparish.org/ Church of England Parish of Padiham and Hapton]\n*[http://www.padihamtowncouncil.gov.uk/ Padiham Town Council]\n*[http://www.visitburnley.com/padiham.php Visit Padiham]\n*[http://archivecat.lancashire.gov.uk/CalmView/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=UDPA&pos=1 Padiham Urban District Council archive catalogue]\n*{{oscoor gbx|SD7933}}\n\n{{Borough of Burnley}}\n{{Lancashire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Padiham| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Districts in Burnley]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:History of Lancashire]]\n", "name_user": "Bmcln1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePeople", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Padiham"}
{"title_page": "CMON Limited", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = CMON Limited\n| type             = [[Public Corporation]]\n| industry         = [[Miniature wargaming]] and [[Board game]] publisher\n| subsid           = CMON Inc\n| foundation       = 2001\n| hq_location_country = Singapore\n| key_people       = Chern Ann Ng (CEO), David Doust (co-founder)\n| products         = \n| homepage         = {{URL|www.cmon.com}}\n| footnotes        = \n| revenue = US$17 million <ref>{{cite web |url=http://gem.ednews.hk/listedco/listconews/GEM/2016/1125/GLN20161125003.pdf |title=CMON Limited Prospectus |author=CMON Limited |date=December 2, 2016 |publisher=Hong Kong Stock Exchange }}</ref>\n| revenue_year = 2015\n| logo = File:Logo_CMON.png\n| traded_as = {{SEHK|1792}}\n}}\n'''CMON Limited''', formerly known as '''CoolMiniOrNot''' is a publicly listed miniatures and board game publisher, trading on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange. It also operates a miniatures related site coolminiornot.com <ref>[http://www.similarweb.com/website/coolminiornot.com 6th in the world in the Gaming/Miniatures category according to Similarweb as of May 3rd, 2013]</ref> that features user submitted images of their painted models for voting.\n\n==History==\nCoolMiniOrNot was founded as a community site for posting images of painted miniatures, inspired by [[Hot or Not]] style dating sites.<ref>[http://www.wampforum.com/content.php?r=260-Interview-with-Chern-Ann Interview WAMP interview with Chern Ann Ng, retrieved May 3rd, 2013]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20010720071441/http://www.coolminiornot.com/ Wayback Machine Archive of coolminiornot.com July 20th, 2001 retrieved May 3rd, 2013]</ref>\n\nIt later began publishing board games and miniature games, notable titles include [[Super Dungeon Explore]]<ref>[http://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/92190/super-dungeon-explore Boardgamegeek Super Dungeon Explore listing]</ref> in 2011 and [[Zombicide]]<ref>[http://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/113924/zombicide Boardgamegeek Zombicide listing]</ref> in 2012.\n\nSome of its games are critically acclaimed, with three games (Xenoshyft, Rum and Bones and Blood Rage) making [[The Dice Tower]]'s top 10 games of 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a3FB_oqfo1o |title=Top 10 Games of 2015 |author=The Dice Tower |date=December 15, 2015 |publisher=YouTube }}</ref>\n\nOn December 2, 2016, CMON Limited began publicly trading on the GEM board of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hkex.com.hk/eng/market/partcir/hkscc/2016/Documents/ce301_2016.pdf |title=Stock Admission - New Listing of Securities |author=CMON Limited |date=December 2, 2016 |publisher=Hong Kong Securities Clearing Company Limited }}</ref>\n\nTrading of CMON Ltd was halted on April 1, 2020 after having audit issues.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://icv2.com/articles/news/view/45581/annual-report-delayed-trading-suspended-cmon?fbclid=IwAR1SquWmVuleOhkP4lWL4p3zkaCEXsrXvQNrvRqFetZ93-IG4TgyafmFpxE |title=Annual Report Delayed, Trading Suspended in CMON |author=Milton Griepp |date=April 10, 2020 |publisher=icv2 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www1.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/sehk/2020/0401/2020040100817.pdf |title=Suspension of Trading |date=January 4, 2020 |publisher=SEHK }}</ref>\n\n==Kickstarter activity==\nCoolMiniOrNot has used [[Kickstarter]] with relative success occupying several places in the Most Funded Tabletop Games category.<ref>[https://www.kickstarter.com/discover/advanced?state=successful&category_id=34&sort=most_funded Kickstarter Tabletop Games / Most Funded retrieved June 13, 2015]</ref>  The total amount raised thus far is $38,112,581, and the company actively pursues a strategy of Kickstarter to create new products.<ref>[http://www.icv2.com/articles/news/25446.html ICV2 interview with David Doust]</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ CoolMiniOrNot's Kickstarter projects<ref>[http://www.kickstarter.com/profile/cmon/created